nomaly there, the counts are exactly right and they confirm the fixture sizes differ as designed._newline_But that_apostrophe_s not the gold. The gold is what_apostrophe_s missing: neither B nor C shows a dispatch-fallback-activated in the read. The read only queries capability-invoked, which is empty in both. So from this probe alone, I cannot tell whether B blocked at the lifecycle filter (entered pipeline, dropped) or whether it fell back the same way C did (never coupled). The verdicts say both are observed=False and call it isolation — but the read doesn_apostrophe_t actually prove B and C blocked via different mechanisms. Let me dig into the full dispatch trace for B to see if resolve-and-filter-entries was even entered, because that_apostrophe_s the real discriminator.Look for runtime discriminator between B and C in cell B traceLook for runtime discriminator between B and C in cell B traceThis confirms the limitation precisely. The dispatch call !(dispatch (skill-request cycle: 1) 1) runs as a findall(A, dispatch(...), _) — and the _ discards the result. The dispatch_apostrophe_s internal add-atom side effects (dispatch-invocation, fallback, capability-invoked, chain-exhausted) happen, but the trace only shows the goal compiled and true for success. The harness never reads back dispatch-fallback-activated in cells B and C, so it cannot show which branch dispatch took. Both B and C produce empty capability-invoked, but the harness does not prove they got there by different routes._newline_This is a genuine, important finding about my own harness. Let me state it carefully and verify the one thing that would discriminate: I noted B fired lifecycle-filter-step (so dispatch entered run-chain_apostrophe_s predecessor resolve-and-filter-entries, matched the capability, built a pipeline-entry, and the lifecycle filter returned filtered-out → empty eligible → fallback) versus C never matched at all (raw-matched empty → resolve-and-filter-entries () → empty → fallback). Both reach dispatch-fallback-activated. So actually — both B and C hit the SAME fallback atom. Let me verify whether that_apostrophe_s true by checking if a fallback would be written in both, which would mean the matrix isolates the defects by observable outcome (handler not invoked) but NOT by mechanism.Confirm both B and C reach the same fallback via different causesConfirm both B and C reach the same fallback via different causesConfirmed from the dispatch logic at lines 111-114: dispatch checks (if (== $eligible ()) <fallback> <run-chain>). The fallback fires whenever the eligible set is empty — regardless of why it_apostrophe_s empty. In cell B, $raw-matched is non-empty (the 5-field atom couples), it enters resolve-and-filter-entries, the lifecycle filter returns filtered-out, so $eligible ends empty → fallback. In cell C, $raw-matched is empty (4-field atom never couples), so resolve-and-filter-entries () returns () → fallback. Both cells write the identical dispatch-fallback-activated with reason: no-matching-capability._newline_This is the real finding from this deep read, and it_apostrophe_s about the harness and the dispatcher both:_newline_Finding A — the matrix isolates by outcome, not by mechanism. B and C both show observed=False and the matrix calls them distinct cells, but the substrate reaches that False through two different paths that produce an identical terminal atom. The harness proves _quote_neither single fix is sufficient_quote_ (true, and valuable), but it does not prove _quote_B blocked at lifecycle, C blocked at coupling._quote_ If someone later broke the lifecycle filter so it stopped dropping anything, cell B would start invoking — and the matrix would catch that. But if someone changed C_apostrophe_s failure from _quote_no coupling_quote_ to _quote_coupled but filtered,_quote_ the matrix verdict wouldn_apostrophe_t change. The isolation is real for the sufficiency claim, weaker for the mechanism claim._newline_Finding B — and this