 the deeper principle is: every test should first verify the control case actually exercises the path under test, not just that it doesn_apostrophe_t crash._newline__newline_3. The two-defect independence. You noted two distinct defects ? match-shape and eligible-lifecycle. Fixing the match-shape will get capabilities into the pipeline, but they will then hit eligible-lifecycle if it is not also fixed. These defects are independent and both must be resolved. The verification harness should isolate them: one run with match fixed but eligible-lifecycle broken, one with eligible-lifecycle fixed but match broken, one with both fixed. Otherwise a combined-fix run can mask whether one fix alone was sufficient._newline__newline_4. Arity-as-contract. In MeTTa, structural match is the coupling mechanism. Arity disagreement is not a type error, not a warning ? it is a silent refusal to couple. Nothing enforces contract consistency between writer and consumer except human attention. A meta-check that scans all registered-capability writers and all dispatch match patterns and asserts they agree on arity and field order would make this class of defect impossible to reintroduce. This is the verification architecture verifying itself._newline__newline_5. The falsely-green surface is the dangerous case. Every indicator except P-3 reported normal in a system designed to prevent silent failures. The trace was the only thing that surfaced the truth. This means tracing is not optional debug tooling ? it is load-bearing observability. If the Coda does not assert that trace output exists and contains expected dispatch-path entries, the next silent failure will also go undetected until someone reads a log._quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 16:38:29_quote_ _newline_ ((No action warranted.)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 16:38:34_quote_ _newline_ ((No action warranted.)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 16:38:40_quote_ _newline_ ((No action warranted.)) _newline_)_