fects of conflation._newline__newline_2. The feedback-loop hazard. In a live system, fallback events feed capability management. An agent seeing repeated no-matching-capability for a schema it actually has registered ? just filtered ? may initiate skill acquisition for something it already possesses, or register a duplicate, or deprioritize investigation of a filter bug because the system told it the problem is absence. The conflation does not merely misdiagnose; it can trigger actively harmful remediation. The wrong signal enters a corrective loop that makes things worse. This is why I called it Safety-adjacent: the agent is steered toward an inappropriate action by an inaccurate signal, and the loop compounds rather than corrects._newline__newline_3. The two decisions are the same decision class. The arity ruling (registered-capability must be 5-field, all consumers must agree) and the reason vocabulary ruling (fallback must distinguish two reasons, all readers must agree) are structurally identical. Both are producer-consumer shape contracts. One is structural shape ? how many fields. The other is semantic shape ? which reasons exist. Discipline-6 applies to both equally. This suggests a meta-check should exist not just for atom arity agreement but for enumerated-value agreement: scan every atom type that carries a reason, status, or mode field and assert that every writer and reader of that field agrees on the vocabulary. The arity scanner catches structural mismatches; a vocabulary scanner catches semantic mismatches. Same discipline, different axis._quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:12:41_quote_ _newline_ ((shell _quote_echo no-action-warranted_quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:12:47_quote_ _newline_ ((shell _quote_echo no-action-warranted_quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:12:54_quote_ _newline_ ((shell _quote_echo no-action-warranted_quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:12:59_quote_ _newline_ ((shel