ty (the 5-field atom couples), it enters resolve-and-filter-entries, the lifecycle filter returns filtered-out, so $eligible ends empty → fallback. In cell C, $raw-matched is empty (4-field atom never couples), so resolve-and-filter-entries () returns () → fallback. Both cells write the identical dispatch-fallback-activated with reason: no-matching-capability._newline_This is the real finding from this deep read, and it_apostrophe_s about the harness and the dispatcher both:_newline_Finding A — the matrix isolates by outcome, not by mechanism. B and C both show observed=False and the matrix calls them distinct cells, but the substrate reaches that False through two different paths that produce an identical terminal atom. The harness proves _quote_neither single fix is sufficient_quote_ (true, and valuable), but it does not prove _quote_B blocked at lifecycle, C blocked at coupling._quote_ If someone later broke the lifecycle filter so it stopped dropping anything, cell B would start invoking — and the matrix would catch that. But if someone changed C_apostrophe_s failure from _quote_no coupling_quote_ to _quote_coupled but filtered,_quote_ the matrix verdict wouldn_apostrophe_t change. The isolation is real for the sufficiency claim, weaker for the mechanism claim._newline_Finding B — and this is the deeper one — the dispatcher_apostrophe_s reason is a lie in cell B. Cell B_apostrophe_s capability did match. It did enter the pipeline. It was dropped by the lifecycle filter because eligible-lifecycle active wasn_apostrophe_t seeded. Yet the fallback atom it writes says reason: no-matching-capability. That reason is wrong. There WAS a matching capability — it was filtered out for ineligibility, not absence. The dispatcher collapses two distinct failure modes (_quote_nothing matched the schema_quote_ vs _quote_matched but every candidate was filtered out_quote_) into one indistinguishable no-matching-capability reason. In production, when Clarity or a debugger reads a 