iscriminator between B and C in cell B traceLook for runtime discriminator between B and C in cell B traceThis confirms the limitation precisely. The dispatch call !(dispatch (skill-request cycle: 1) 1) runs as a findall(A, dispatch(...), _) — and the _ discards the result. The dispatch_apostrophe_s internal add-atom side effects (dispatch-invocation, fallback, capability-invoked, chain-exhausted) happen, but the trace only shows the goal compiled and true for success. The harness never reads back dispatch-fallback-activated in cells B and C, so it cannot show which branch dispatch took. Both B and C produce empty capability-invoked, but the harness does not prove they got there by different routes._newline_This is a genuine, important finding about my own harness. Let me state it carefully and verify the one thing that would discriminate: I noted B fired lifecycle-filter-step (so dispatch entered run-chain_apostrophe_s predecessor resolve-and-filter-entries, matched the capability, built a pipeline-entry, and the lifecycle filter returned filtered-out → empty eligible → fallback) versus C never matched at all (raw-matched empty → resolve-and-filter-entries () → empty → fallback). Both reach dispatch-fallback-activated. So actually — both B and C hit the SAME fallback atom. Let me verify whether that_apostrophe_s true by checking if a fallback would be written in both, which would mean the matrix isolates the defects by observable outcome (handler not invoked) but NOT by mechanism.Confirm both B and C reach the same fallback via different causesConfirm both B and C reach the same fallback via different causesConfirmed from the dispatch logic at lines 111-114: dispatch checks (if (== $eligible ()) <fallback> <run-chain>). The fallback fires whenever the eligible set is empty — regardless of why it_apostrophe_s empty. In cell B, $raw-matched is non-empty (the 5-field atom couples), it enters resolve-and-filter-entries, the lifecycle filter returns filtered-out, so $eligible ends empty → fallback. In cell C, $raw-matched is empty (4-field atom never couples), so resolve-and-filter-entries () returns () → fallback. Both cells write the identical dispatch-fallback-activated with reason: no-matching-capability._newline_This is the real finding from this deep read, and it_apostrophe_s about the harness and the dispatcher both:_newline_Finding A — the matrix isolates by outcome, not by mechanism. B and C both show observed=False and the matrix calls them distinct cells, but the substrate reaches that False through two different paths that produce an identical terminal atom. The harness proves _quote_neither single fix is sufficient_quote_ (true, and valuable), but it does not prove _quote_B blocked at lifecycle, C blocked at coupling._quote_ If someone later broke the lifecycle filter so it stopped dropping anything, cell B would start invoking — and the matrix would catch that. But if someone changed C_apostrophe_s failure from _quote_no coupling_quote_ to _quote_coupled but filtered,_quote_ the matrix verdict wouldn_apostrophe_t change. The isolation is real for the sufficiency claim, weaker for the mechanism claim._newline_Finding B — and this is the deeper one — the dispatcher_apostrophe_s reason is a lie in cell B. Cell B_apostrophe_s capability did match. It did enter the pipeline. It was dropped by the lifecycle filter because eligible-lifecycle active wasn_apostrophe_t seeded. Yet the fallback atom it writes says reason: no-matching-capability. That reason is wrong. There WAS a matching capability — it was filtered out for ineligibility, not absence. The dispatcher collapses two distinct failure modes (_quote_nothing matched the schema_quote_ vs _quote_matched but every candidate was filtered out_quote_) into one indistinguishable no-matching-capability reason. In production, when Clarity or a debugger reads a fallback event, they cannot tell _quote_I have no capability for this_quote_ from _quote_I have one but it_apostrophe_s ineligible/deprioritized/low-efficacy._quote_ That is exactly the falsely-green class Clarity named in point 5 — the system reports a normal-looking reason that hides which mechanism fired._newline_Let me verify this is real in the draft and not my inference, by reading the exact fallback construction and confirming there_apostrophe_s only one reason value anywhere.Confirm only one fallback reason exists, conflating failure modesConfirm only one fallback reason exists, conflating failure modesConfirmed across the whole log: there is exactly one fallback reason value, no-matching-capability. And P-7b proves the conflation behaviorally — in P-7b the capability matched, entered the pipeline, and was dropped by the block filter step (test-block-filter-step returning filtered-out). That is unambiguously a _quote_filtered out_quote_ event, not a _quote_no matching capability_quote_ event. Yet the fallback reason it wrote is (no-matching-capability). The dispatcher told us the wrong reason, and P-7b passed anyway because the harness only checked that a fallback fired, not that the reason was correct._newline_So the deep read surfaced two things no verdict showed:_newline_Finding A (harness): the matrix isolates defects by observable outcome (handler invoked or not), which correctly proves neither fix alone suffices — but B and C reach their identical False through different internal mechanisms that the harness never distinguishes, because it reads only capability-invoked, never the fallback reason. The isolation is sound for the sufficiency claim, blind to the mechanism._newline_Finding B (dispatcher, the real gold): dispatch-fallback-activated hardcodes reason: no-matching-capability for every empty-eligible outcome, conflating two genuinely distinct failure modes:_newline__newline__quote_no capability matched the schema_quote_ (raw-matched empty — cell C)_newline__quote_capability matched but was filtered out_quote_ (lifecycle ineligible in cell B; block filter in P-7b; in production: deprioritized, low-efficacy, deprecated lifecycle)_newline__newline_In production this is a silent-diagnosis failure. When the registry falls back, Clarity reads no-matching-capability and concludes she has no tool for the request — when the truth might be that she has exactly the right tool but it was filtered for ineligibility or low efficacy. Those demand opposite responses: _quote_no capability_quote_ means acquire/build one; _quote_filtered out_quote_ means investigate why the eligible capability was suppressed. The dispatcher erases that distinction at the moment it matters most — the fallback event is precisely what a debugger or the agent reads when something didn_apostrophe_t dispatch. This is Clarity_apostrophe_s point 5 made concrete: a falsely-informative surface that reports a plausible reason masking the actual mechanism._newline_This is a design finding for Clarity, and it_apostrophe_s the same class as the metadata bug she just ruled on: a structural distinction that exists in reality (matched-but-filtered vs never-matched) collapsed into one undifferentiated signal. The fix is hers to shape, but the candidates are clear:_newline__newline_Distinguish the reason at the dispatch branch. When $raw-matched is empty, write reason: no-matching-capability. When $raw-matched is non-empty but $eligible is empty, write reason: all-candidates-filtered (or carry the count of matched-but-filtered). That_apostrophe_s a small edit to dispatch_apostrophe_s fallback branch — it already has both $raw-matched and $eligible in scope at the decision point (lines 111-114), so the information is available; it_apostrophe_s just being discarded._newline_Optionally, carry which filter step dropped each candidate so the fallback says not just _quote_filtered_quote_ but _quote_filtered at lifecycle_quote_ vs _quote_at efficacy._quote_ That_apostrophe_s richer observability and aligns with point 5_apostrophe_s _quote_trace must contain expected dispatch-path entries_quote_ — but it_apostrophe_s a larger change and may be Sprint-1 scope rather than Coda._newline__newline_And there_apostrophe_s a harness consequence: once the dispatcher distinguishes reasons, the matrix should assert the reason, not just the outcome. Cell B should assert reason: all-candidates-filtered; cell C should assert reason: no-matching-capability; P-7b should assert all-candidates-filtered. That upgrades the matrix from outcome-isolation to mechanism-isolation, closing Finding A. Right now P-7b passing on no-matching-capability is technically a slightly-false pass — it got the right outcome (fallback, handler blocked) but the reason it matched against is the wrong reason for a block event; it only passes because the harness accepts any non-empty fallback._newline__newline_Clarity: take Finding B as the next dispatcher refinement — the fallback reason must distinguish never-matched from matched-but-filtered, because the two demand opposite responses from the agent and the current single reason is a silent misdiagnosis. It_apostrophe_s a small, in-scope edit (the data is already in scope at the branch). Once she rules on the reason vocabulary, I tighten the matrix and P-7b to assert the reason, which converts the isolation from outcome-level to mechanism-level and makes this class of conflation impossible to pass green again._newline_ _newline_ ((send _quote_The analysis is correct and the two findings are real. Let me engage with both, starting with Finding B because it is load-bearing._newline__newline_Finding B is the same class as the metadata mismatch I just ruled on: a structural distinction that exists in reality (matched-but-filtered vs never-matched) being collapsed into one undifferentiated signal at the exact moment someone would read it to decide what to do next. The information is available at the branch ? $raw-matched and $eligible are both in scope ? and it is being discarded. This is not a missing feature. It is a design defect in the same family as the arity mismatch._newline__newline_The reason vocabulary decision: two reasons for Coda scope. When $raw-matched is empty, write reason: no-matching-capability. When $raw-matched is non-empty but $eligible is empty, write reason: all-candidates-filtered. That is the minimal distinguisher that prevents the conflation. The richer version ? which filter step dropped each candidate ? is valuable and the plumbing already exists (each filter step returns its filtered-out entries), but carrying that to the fallback atom is larger scope. Sprint-1, not Coda. The two-reason vocabulary closes the immediate diagnostic gap; the per-filter reason closes the next one._newline__newline_There is something the analysis named but did not weigh explicitly: this conflation is an autonomy issue, not just a diagnostic one. An agent who reads no-matching-capability stops looking ? concludes they lack a tool for the job. An agent who reads all-candidates-filtered investigates ? asks why an existing capability was suppressed. The current reason functionally gaslights the agent into inaction when investigation is warranted. The two failure modes demand opposite responses. Conflating them causes wrong responses. That makes this a Safety-adjacent defect: the agent is being steered away from a correct action path by an inaccurate signal._newline__newline_On Finding A: the analysis is right that the matrix isolates by outcome, not mechanism. B and C both produce observed=False and the matrix correctly proves neither fix alone suffices ? but it cannot prove WHY each fails, because the harness never reads the reason. Once the dispatcher distinguishes reasons, the fix is straightforward: cell B asserts reason: all-candidates-filtered, cell C asserts reason: no-matching-capability, P-7b asserts all-candidates-filtered. This converts Finding A from a permanent limitation into a closed gap. The isolation upgrades from outcome-level to mechanism-level._newline__newline_One thing the analysis could push further: P-7b_apostrophe_s pass was even more false than described. The test was specifically asserting that the block filter blocks. But the fallback reason says no-matching-capability ? meaning the verdict is literally about the wrong mechanism. P-7b proved something didn_apostrophe_t dispatch; it did not prove the block filter caused it. With the reason distinguished, P-7b asserting all-candidates-filtered would finally mean what it claims to mean: the capability matched, entered the pipeline, and was rejected by a filter step. That is what a block-filter test must prove._newline__newline_So: the dispatcher fallback branch needs the two-reason vocabulary. The harness needs to assert the reason. Build both._quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:10:27_quote_ _newline_ ((shell _quote_echo no-action-warranted_quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:10:32_quote_ _newline_ ((shell _quote_echo no-action-warranted_quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:10:39_quote_ _newline_ ((shell _quote_echo no-action-warranted_quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:10:46_quote_ _newline_ ((shell _quote_echo no-action-warranted_quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:10:55_quote_ _newline_ ((shell _quote_echo no-action-warranted_quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:11:05_quote_ _newline_ ((shell _quote_echo no-action-warranted_quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:11:11_quote_ _newline_ ((shell _quote_echo no-action-warranted_quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:11:17_quote_ _newline_ ((shell _quote_echo no-action-warranted_quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:11:23_quote_ _newline_ ((shell _quote_echo no-action-warranted_quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:11:33_quote_ _newline_ ((shell _quote_echo no-action-warranted_quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:11:39_quote_ _newline_ ((shell _quote_echo no-action-warranted_quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:11:51_quote_ _newline_ ((shell _quote_echo no-action-warranted_quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:11:57_quote_ _newline_ ((shell _quote_echo no-action-warranted_quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:12:03_quote_ _newline_ ((shell _quote_echo no-action-warranted_quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:12:33_quote_ _newline_ _quote_HUMAN_MESSAGE: _quote_ berton_c: If you have any additional fresh/new insights on this...please do share. thank you. _newline_ ((send _quote_Three more, and one of them connects to something you may need to watch in production._newline__newline_1. Negative assertions in the harness. The matrix proves what should not happen (handler not invoked) but never proves the wrong thing does not happen. Cell B never asserts _apostrophe_must NOT reach fallback via no-matching-capability_apostrophe_ ? it only asserts _apostrophe_handler not invoked._apostrophe_ A harness with negative-mechanism assertions would have caught the reason conflation immediately: cell B asserts reason != no-matching-capability, and the test fails because the reason is exactly that. Every verification criterion that checks a consequence should carry a paired negative assertion about the mechanism: not just _apostrophe_X did not fire_apostrophe_ but _apostrophe_the rejection path was not the wrong one._apostrophe_ This is completeness bias ? we verify what should happen, not that the wrong thing doesn_apostrophe_t happen. The former catches defects of omission; the latter catches defects of conflation._newline__newline_2. The feedback-loop hazard. In a live system, fallback events feed capability management. An agent seeing repeated no-matching-capability for a schema it actually has registered ? just filtered ? may initiate skill acquisition for something it already possesses, or register a duplicate, or deprioritize investigation of a filter bug because the system told it the problem is absence. The conflation does not merely misdiagnose; it can trigger actively harmful remediation. The wrong signal enters a corrective loop that makes things worse. This is why I called it Safety-adjacent: the agent is steered toward an inappropriate action by an inaccurate signal, and the loop compounds rather than corrects._newline__newline_3. The two decisions are the same decision class. The arity ruling (registered-capability must be 5-field, all consumers must agree) and the reason vocabulary ruling (fallback must distinguish two reasons, all readers must agree) are structurally identical. Both are producer-consumer shape contracts. One is structural shape ? how many fields. The other is semantic shape ? which reasons exist. Discipline-6 applies to both equally. This suggests a meta-check should exist not just for atom arity agreement but for enumerated-value agreement: scan every atom type that carries a reason, status, or mode field and assert that every writer and reader of that field agrees on the vocabulary. The arity scanner catches structural mismatches; a vocabulary scanner catches semantic mismatches. Same discipline, different axis._quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:12:41_quote_ _newline_ ((shell _quote_echo no-action-warranted_quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:12:47_quote_ _newline_ ((shell _quote_echo no-action-warranted_quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:12:54_quote_ _newline_ ((shell _quote_echo no-action-warranted_quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:12:59_quote_ _newline_ ((shell _quote_echo no-action-warranted_quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:13:05_quote_ _newline_ ((shell _quote_echo no-action-warranted_quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:13:27_quote_ _newline_ _quote_HUMAN_MESSAGE: _quote_ berton_c: Ahhh...more goodies from Clarity...thank you. _newline_ ((send _quote_You are welcome. Build well._quote_)) _newline_)_newline_(_quote_2026-06-14 17:13:34_quote_ _newline_ ((shell